[[File:Tahrir Square on July 29 2011.jpg|thumb|Hundreds of thousands of people protesting in Tahrir Square on 29 July 2011]]
A Facebook page entitled "The Second Egyptian Revolution of Rage" read: "Seeing that the situation, under the leadership of the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces, is only going from bad to worse, and since the council has proven from day one that public pressure is the most effective policy for achieving the demands of the legitimate revolution, we have decided to take to the streets and squares [once again] and demonstrate throughout Egypt until our demands are met..."<ref name="memri1">{{cite news|title=Disappointed with Revolution's Gains, Egyptians Renew Protests|url=http://www.memri.org/report/en/0/0/0/0/0/0/5429.htm|accessdate=5 July 2011|newspaper=http://www.memri.org/|date=3 July 2011}}</ref> On the 1 July, tens of thousands of protesters gathered for what they termed the "Friday of Retribution"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailynewsegypt.com/egypt/thousands-demonstrate-on-friday-of-retribution.html |title=Thousands demonstrate on 'Friday of Retribution' |publisher=Thedailynewsegypt.com |accessdate=10 July 2011}}</ref> in Suez, Alexandria and Tahrir Square in Cairo to voice frustrations with the ruling Supreme Council of the Armed Forces for what they perceived to be the slow pace of change five months after Mubarak's ousting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://channel6newsonline.com/2011/07/thousands-of-egyptians-protest-against-police-brutality/ |title=Channel 6 News Â» Thousands of Egyptians protest against police brutality |publisher=Channel6newsonline.com |accessdate=2 July 2011}}</ref>
